## 9. `intsructions.txt` (System Prompt) — Deep Review

**Rating: 9.5/10 — Near-perfect system prompt.**

### Strengths
- The dual-document workflow is clearly defined: original plan first, overlay second
- The severity enforcement rules are unambiguous
- The "WHAT NOT TO DO" section preemptively eliminates the most common AI failure modes ("should I apply the fix?" → just apply it)
- Package naming convention included verbatim — AI can't get it wrong
- Asks for handoff summary in exact format — reproducible, parseable

### Issues

| # | Issue |
|---|-------|
| I-1 | Line 96: "Start each session by asking me: 'Which day or section are we working on today?'" — This is correct for a fresh session, but session prompts already provide this context inline. On Day 8, pasting the session prompt after this instruction means the AI asks the question AND has the answer simultaneously. Minor friction but could confuse the flow. Consider: "If the day is not stated in my first message, ask: Which day are we working on?" |
| I-2 | No mention of the SpecKit agents in the system prompt. The prompt is written as if Copilot is in free-chat mode. In practice, the user switches between `@speckit.plan`, `@speckit.tasks`, `@speckit.implement` etc. This prompt would be read by whichever agent is active. Verify that each SpecKit agent's own `.agent.md` also reads `copilot-instructions.md` — if agents don't reference it, the master config is only active for free-chat mode. |
| I-3 | The final checklist tracking instruction (Point 5) says "At the end of each week (Day 7, Day 14, Day 21), run through the checklist." But Day 14's session prompt doesn't exist (Days 11–21 missing). This weekly checkpoint will be missed unless a Day 14 prompt is created. |

